    {
      "action": "journal-upsert",
      "id": "v25-bot-excl-climbing",
      "strategy_id": "v25-bot-excl-climbing",
      "cohort_label": "v25",
      "hypothesis": "v21-bottom-excluded is the front-runner at n=128, net +4.10 SOL, but 44 SL fires (34%) are dragging the avg. Hypothesis: adding climbing_t30_t45 (recovery_t45_above_t30=1) at entry will pre-filter out the trades destined to hit SL — the C5 climbing gate excludes tokens whose price is dropping between t30 and t45, which is exactly the population that goes on to hit -30% SL. Trade-off: ~50% lower n, entry at T+60 instead of T+30. If the climbing filter cuts SL rate from 34% to ~18% while keeping TP rate similar, net SOL per trade should rise sharply.",
      "prediction": {
        "target_net_sol": 2.5,
        "target_sol_per_mo": 15,
        "target_drop_top3": 0.5,
        "target_n": 80,
        "target_days": 21,
        "kill_criterion": "n>=40 and net_sol<-1"
      },
      "status": "OPEN"
    },
    {
      "action": "journal-upsert",
      "id": "v25-bot-excl-calm",
      "strategy_id": "v25-bot-excl-calm",
      "cohort_label": "v25",
      "hypothesis": "v21-bottom-excluded variant: add sum_abs_returns_0_30 < 60 (realized vol proxy) to exclude whippy pre-entry tokens. Hypothesis: tokens with high pre-entry vol tend to whipsaw — the 30% SL is wide enough that the price spike upward looks like a winner, then a fast pullback hits the stop. Excluding whippy entries should preferentially cut SL count while preserving TP candidates. v17/v18 calm-survivor cohorts (sum_abs<60 + dd>-10) tested positive in early data. Different SL-reduction mechanism than the climbing variant: calmness is a population-shape filter (orthogonal to direction), climbing is a directional filter.",
      "prediction": {
        "target_net_sol": 2.0,
        "target_sol_per_mo": 10,
        "target_drop_top3": 0.4,
        "target_n": 80,
        "target_days": 21,
        "kill_criterion": "n>=40 and net_sol<-1"
      },
      "status": "OPEN"
    },
    {
      "action": "journal-upsert",
      "id": "v25-bot-excl-breakeven",
      "strategy_id": "v25-bot-excl-breakeven",
      "cohort_label": "v25",
      "hypothesis": "v21-bottom-excluded with breakevenStopPct=20 — same filters and TP/SL grid, but once a trade's HWM hits +20%, the SL line moves to 0%. Hypothesis: of the 44 current SL fires, some fraction touched +20% before bleeding back; those convert from -30% SL outcomes to 0% TO outcomes. Doesn't reduce SL COUNT but reduces SL MAGNITUDE on those trades. Cost: trades that briefly hit +20%, pull back, then would have recovered to a TP — get cut at 0% instead. If even 1/3 of current SL trades touched +20% first, this saves ~4 SOL of losses vs the baseline +4.10 SOL net.",
      "prediction": {
        "target_net_sol": 5.5,
        "target_sol_per_mo": 25,
        "target_drop_top3": 0.8,
        "target_n": 150,
        "target_days": 14,
        "kill_criterion": "n>=75 and net_sol<-1"
      },
      "status": "OPEN"
    },
    {
      "action": "journal-upsert",
      "id": "v25-bot-excl-tp150",
      "strategy_id": "v25-bot-excl-tp150",
      "cohort_label": "v25",
      "hypothesis": "v21-bottom-excluded with TP=150 (was 100) and SL=25 (was 30). Same filter universe. Hypothesis: top leaderboard combos use TP/SL ratios closer to 6:1 (TP=150/SL=25) than 3:1 (TP=100/SL=30) — e.g. `vel 20-50 + climbing_t30_t45` at n=131, opt +9.91% with TP=150/SL=25. The current strategy only captures 10% TP — many of those tokens that hit +100% keep running to +200%+. Wider TP captures the right tail while tighter SL caps losses. Tradeoff: trades that would have hit TP=100 keep running; some reverse and hit SL. Net effect should be positive if the right-tail-strength signal that the bottom-excluded universe selects for is real.",
      "prediction": {
        "target_net_sol": 5.0,
        "target_sol_per_mo": 20,
        "target_drop_top3": 0.7,
        "target_n": 120,
        "target_days": 14,
        "kill_criterion": "n>=75 and net_sol<-1"
      },
      "status": "OPEN"
    },
    {
      "action": "journal-upsert",
      "id": "v25-bot-excl-mono",
      "strategy_id": "v25-bot-excl-mono",
      "cohort_label": "v25",
      "hypothesis": "v21-bottom-excluded + monotonicity_0_30 > 0.5 overlay. Hypothesis: v21-bottom-excluded is unusual in being pure exclusion (top5/dd/vel/age) with no positive feature stacked. Leaderboard's strongest combos pair an exclusion with a positive feature like mono or climbing. Adding mono>0.5 (Cohen's d=0.42 — the strongest single-feature signal we have) should shift the population from `not the worst` to `trends positive AND not the worst`. Should compound the two effects without over-narrowing — mono>0.5 fires on ~25-50% of rows so coverage is reasonable.",
      "prediction": {
        "target_net_sol": 3.0,
        "target_sol_per_mo": 15,
        "target_drop_top3": 0.5,
        "target_n": 100,
        "target_days": 21,
        "kill_criterion": "n>=50 and net_sol<-1"
      },
      "status": "OPEN"
    },
    {
      "action": "journal-upsert",
      "id": "v25-bot-excl-vel2050",
      "strategy_id": "v25-bot-excl-vel2050",
      "cohort_label": "v25",
      "hypothesis": "v21-bottom-excluded with vel<200 replaced by vel in [20, 50] band. Hypothesis: vel 20-50 is the magic band on the leaderboard — `vel 20-50 + dd>-10%` (n=128, opt +5.42%) AND `vel 20-50 + climbing_t30_t45` (n=131, opt +9.91%, current research baseline) both clear promotion. The current strategy's vel<200 captures the whole curve including slow/fast outliers; concentrating bets on the proven band should compound the exclusion + velocity effects. Tradeoff: ~40% lower trade count, loses the vel<20 and vel 50-200 trades currently in v21-bottom-excluded.",
      "prediction": {
